birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| nationality   = [[American nationality law|American]]\n| field         = [[Sculpture]]\n| training      = [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]];  [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| movement      = \n| works  = ''Freedom Sculpture'', ''[[United States Air Force Memorial]] Honor Guard'', ''Knowledge is Power'', ''Payne Stewart'' at Pinehurst Golf Course\n}}\n'''Zenos Frudakis''' (born 1951) is an American [[sculptors|sculptor]] whose subjects include portraits of living and historical individuals and poetic/philosophical sculpture. He lives and works near [[Philadelphia]]. His works include those at [[Brookgreen Gardens]],<ref>Robin R. Salmon, ''Brookgreen Gardens Sculpture'' (Brookgreen Gardens, 1993), v. 2, pp. 188-91.</ref> the [[Lotos Club]] of New York City,<ref name=\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\">''The Lotos Experience, The Tradition Continues'' (Lotos Club, 1995), pp. 34-35.</ref> the Utsukushi ga-hara Open Air Museum in [[Japan]],<ref>''Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum,'' Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> the [[National Academy of Design]],<ref>When an artist is voted into membership in the National Academy the Academy accepts a work of art from that artist; Frudakis's work was ''Sheila'', a life-size bronze bust.</ref> and the [[U.S. Embassy]] in [[Pretoria]], [[South Africa]]<ref>Gene Freedman, \"The Unveiling of a Memorial,\" ''USIA World'', April 1989, pp. 10-11. See also \"Hope and Glory,\" ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Sunday March 12, 1989, cover and pp. 4H-5H; \"Martin Luther King Jr Is Remembered,\" ''Herald International Tribune'', January 17, 1989, front page; and \"Bust of Dr. King,\" ''Washington Post'', January 17, 1989, p. 1.</ref>\n[[File:Freedom Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|650px|left|The Freedom Sculpture with sculptor Zenos Frudakis]]\n[[File:Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture.jpg|thumb|Martin Luther King and Freedom sculpture]]\n[[File:Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis. Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Japan.jpg|thumb|Reaching sculpture with Zenos Frudakis at the Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum in Japan.]]\n\n\n\n== Biography ==\nZenos' father, born in [[Greece]], came to the U.S. as a boy. The oldest of five children growing up in Greek culture, Zenos admired, respected, and was drawn to Greek sculpture. Greek art influenced his aesthetic vision; additional inspiration came from sculptors [[Michelangelo]], [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini|Bernini]], [[Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux|Carpeaux]] and [[Auguste Rodin|Rodin]]. The poetry of [[T. S. Eliot|Eliot]], [[Robert Frost|Frost]], [[Theodore Roethke|Roethke]] and [[Robert Graves|Graves]], is important to Zenos, as is philosophy.\n\n\nBorn in 1951 in [[San Francisco]], Frudakis was raised in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Gary, Indiana]], where he worked in the steel mills. He began drawing at a very young age, and in 1972 came to Philadelphia to study at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]. He studied sculpture with two [[Prix de Rome]] winners: his elder brother, sculptor Evangelos Frudakis, and painter James Hanes. At the [[University of Pennsylvania]], he earned bachelor's and master's degrees in Fine Art.<ref>Sarah Blackman, \"Sculpting a Life\" (feature article on Frudakis), ''The Pennsylvania Gazette'', Class of '82, November/December 2002, p. 3.</ref>\n\n\n==International Sculptures==\n* ''[[Reaching (sculpture)|Reaching]]''. Two figures (bronze | 7ft) Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, [[Japan]]. 3rd Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, July 20, 1990.<ref>Henry, Jean \"Contemporary Figurative Sculpture,\" ''The National Sculpture Society Celebrates the Figure'' (National Sculpture Society, 1987), pp. 52-53.</ref><ref>{{Cite web| author= The Hakone Open-Air Museum | url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/53f662b0e4b083b394ab3f14/t/55110825e4b03d839644c042/1427179557796/19900124.Reaching.HakoneLetter.jpg | title= \u201cLetter to Zenos Frudakis\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (bronze | 16ft) Imperial War Museum, Duxford, [[England]]. Dedication 2018.<ref>Imperial War Museum. \u201cMemorial Honor Guard\u201d IWM, Duxford, Cambridgeshire, England.</ref>\n* ''Martin Luther King and Freedom''. Public sculpture (bronze) Peace Garden, University of New South Wales, [[Sydney, Australia]]. Dedication October 19, 2018.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia. </ref>\n* ''[[Lois Browne-Evans|Hon. Dame Lois Browne-Evans]]. Statue (bronze | life-size) Justice Center, Dame Lois Browne Evans Building (Police/Justice Center) [[Hamilton, Bermuda]]. Dedication June 2011.<ref>Aarabdhekivuc, Nadia, The Royal Gazette, \u201cNew Police, Court Building Formally Opened\u201d June 13, 2011. Bermuda. Retrieved 2020-03-29.</ref> \n* ''[[Arnold Palmer]]''. Statue (bronze | over-life-size) Tralee Golf Club, Tralee, County Kerry, [[Ireland]]. Dedication September 10, 2007.<ref>Mavros, Larissa, University of New South Wales, Sydney Newsroom, \u201cBust of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Joins Gallery of Human Rights Icons at UNSW Sydney\u201d October 19, 2018. Sydney, Australia.</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis|Dr. Constantine Papadakis]]''. Drexel University President, Portrait bust (bronze | life size) Town Square, Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication July 24, 2010.<ref>DrexelNow, \u201cTown Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\u201d Drexel University, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, July 20, 2010.</ref>\n* ''Lamby (Abigail), Irish Wolfhound''. Bronze (life-size | 12ft x 11ft) Old Bladbean Stud Garden, Canterbury, [[Kent, England]].<ref>Harpur, Marcus, Country Life \u201cWhere Art Imitates Life\u201d p.44-48, UK, August 5, 2015.</ref>\n*''[[Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.]], [[South Africa]]'' (Bronze portrait bust, granite base | life size) U.S. Embassy, [[Pretoria, South Africa]]. Dedication: January 16, 1989. <ref>Friedmann, Gene, ''USIA World'',''The Unveiling of a Memorial'', April 1989.</ref>\n\n[[File:Payne Stewart by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Payne Stewart sculpture at Pinehust by Zenos Frudakis.]]\n[[File:Benjamin Franklin Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Zenos Frudakis sculpting Benjamin Franklin.]]\n\n\n\n==American Sculptures==\nIn a career spanning over four decades, Frudakis has produced monumental figures such as the [[United States Air Force Memorial]] ''Honor Guard''<ref name=air-force_memorial>Col. Walter Boyne, ''Soaring to Glory, The United States Air Force Memorial'' (for the Air Force Memorial Foundation by the Donning Company, 2007), Chapter 7, \"A Perfect Partnership,\" pp. 80-93. See also \"Guard Honored,\" ''The Academy Spirit'', United States Air Force Academy, Colorado, v. 47, no. 40 (October 5, 2007), p. 1.</ref> Installed at the Arlington National Cemetery, and ''Freedom in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref>''Art Business News'', September 2001, front page photograph.</ref>\n\n\n===Monumental Sculptures===\n* ''Freedom Sculpture''. Monument (Bronze | 20ft x 8ft | 7,000lbs) 16th and Vine Streets, [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. Completed 2000. Dedication June 18, 2001.<ref>Sculpture Review, ''\u201cChanging the American Landscape,\u201d'' Fall 2001, Vol.L, No.3, p.32, [[National Sculpture Society]], [[New York, New York]].</ref>\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Knowledge is Power''. Monument (Bronze | 8ft x 15ft | 1,500lbs) Over 30 portraits from intellectual history, two 8ft figures free standing. Relief wall portraits: [[Harriet Tubman]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], [[Rachel Carson]], [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]], [[Charles Darwin|Darwin]], [[Albert Einstein]], [[Alan Turing]], [[John Muir]], [[Thoreau]], [[James Hall]]{{dn|date=April 2020}}. [[Rowan University]], [[Glassboro, New Jersey]]. Dedication Nov. 21, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Rowan University Libraries, Public Art.  | url=https://publicart.rowan.edu/sculptures/knowledge-is-power-2014/ | title= \u201cKnowledge Is Power\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.'', Monument (Bronze portrait bust, granite base / 5ft / 685lbs) Martin Luther King Park, J. Lewis Crozer Library, Chester, Pennsylvania. Dedication November 23, 2010. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Chester City, Chester\u2019s Park System.  | url=https://www.chestercity.com/departments/parks-recreation/chesters-park-system/ | title= Martin Luther King Park |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* ''The Path to Manhood'', Monument (Bronze | Over-life-size) Perot Quadrangle, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Mark%27s_School_of_Texas  St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas], [[Dallas, Texas]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= St. Mark\u2019s School of Texas, David W. Dini, Headmaster. | url=https://www.smtexas.org/2016-2017/hmremarks | title= Remarks from the Headmaster |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n\n===Memorials===\n* ''[[Honor Guard|U.S. Air Force Memorial Honor Guard]]''. Memorial (Bronze | Monument) [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Arlington, Virginia]]. Dedication: October 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Air Force District of Washington.  | url=https://www.afdw.af.mil/heritage/ | title= \u201cAir Force Memorial\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Molly Maguires]] Memorial'' (Bronze | larger-than-life) Molly Maguires Memorial Park, [[Mahanoy City, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: June 21, 2002<ref>{{Cite web| author= Kelly, Joseph Dennis  | url=https://irishamerica.com/2002/02/the-molly-maguires-remembered/ | title= \u201cThe Molly Maguires Remembered\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''The Workers\u2019 Memorial'' (Bronze | 8ft figure, Mayari-r Steel circle, granite base | 2,500 lbs) The Rose Garden, [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. Sponsored by 20 unions, 15 non-union industries, 3 cities: Allentown, Bethlehem, Easton Pennsylvania. Dedication: April 28, 1991.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Devlin, Ron, The Morning Call. | url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1991-04-28-2802053-story.html | title= \u201cSculpture a Memorial to Workers\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Anthracite Miners\u2019 Memorial''. Relief (Bronze | Left and right panels 6 x 4ft, central panel 8ft sq) Giard Park, [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1996.<ref>{{Cite web| author=The Historical Marker Database | url= https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=86761 | title=Pennsylvania Athracite Miners Memorial |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Nina Simone]]''. Memorial (Bronze, local stone | 8ft figure) Nina Simone Plaza, [[Tryon, North Carolina]]. Dedication: February 21, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web| author= UNC Libraries, Commemorative Landscapes of North Carolina. | url=https://ncpedia.org/monument/nina-simone-sculpture | title= \u201cNina Simone Sculpture\u201d |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''[[Constantine Papadakis | Dr. Constantine \u2018Taki\u2019 Papadakis]].'' Memorial (Bronze | life size) Public Square in Meskla, [[Greece]]. Dedication: July 24, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Drexel University | url =https://drexel.edu/now/archive/2010/July/Town-Square-in-Greece-to-be-Named-for-Late-Drexel-President-Papadakis/ | title=Town Square in Greece to be Named for Late Drexel President Papadakis\n |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* ''Henry L. Bowden''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | over-life-size) Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Dedication: 1991<ref>{{Cite web| author= Emory University | url =http://www.emoryhistory.emory.edu/facts-figures/places/names/atlanta/bowden-hall.html | title=Henry L. Bowden Hall |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* ''Mr. and Mrs Hillenbrand''. Memorial (Bronze bas-relief | life size) Batesville Memorial Public Library, [[Batesville, Indiana]]. Dedication: 1988.\n* ''Veterans Memorial''. Memorial (Bronze | over-life-size) Henry L. Bowden Hall, [[Emory University]], [[Collegeville, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: 1991.\n\n\n===Sports Sculptures===\n====Golf====\n* ''[[Payne Stewart]]''. (Bronze | over-life-size). [[Pinehurst Resort]], [[Pinehurst, North Carolina|Pinehurst]], North Carolina. Dedication: 2001<ref>Lee Pace, ''The Spirit of Pinehurst'' (Pinehurst Resort, 2007), pp. 86-87. See also ''World Golf Courses'' (Chartwell Books, 2007), pp. 144-45.</ref>\n* '' [[Payne Stewart]] '' Statue (Bronze | life size). Coyote Hills Golf Club, [[Fullerton, California]].\n* '' [[Payne Stewart]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Arnold Palmer]] ''. Statue (Bronze | over-life size). Georgia Golf Hall of Fame, [[Augusta, Georgia]]. Dedication: April 9, 1996. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Tomashek, Tom, '' The News Journal''  | url =https://static1.squarespace.com/static/53f662b0e4b083b394ab3f14/t/554a0bc5e4b0e9b67c9e4b99/1430916085963/19960410.Palmer.NewsJournal.jpg| title=Palmer Honored by First of Eight Augusta Statues |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* '' [[Arnold Palmer]] ''. Statue (Bronze | over-life size). [[Arnold Palmer Airport]], [[Latrobe, Pennsylvania]]; Laurel Valley Country Club, Ligonier, Pennsylvania; Tralee, Ireland.\n* '' [[Jack Nicklaus]] '' Statue (Bronze, granite base | 48 inches). [[USGA Museum]], Jack Nicklaus Room, [[Far Hills, New Jersey]]. Dedication: May 27, 2015. <ref>{{Cite web| author= United States Golf Association | url =https://www.usga.org/content/usga/home-page/videos/2015/05/27/150527-nicklaus-room-wrap-4260846447001.html| title=Jack Nicklaus Room Opening|accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* '' [[Jack Nicklaus]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze, stone base | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Jack Nicklaus]] and Dwight Gahm'' Statue (Bronze | life size). [[Valhalla Golf Club]], [[Louisville, Kentucky]]. Dedication: March 8, 2016. <ref>{{Cite web| author= '' Golf Digest'' | url =https://www.golfdigest.com/story/valhalla-golf-club-founder-dies-jack-nicklaus-pays-tribute | title=Valhalla Golf Club Founder Dies, Jack Nicklaus Pays Tribute|accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| author= Zak, Sean, ''Golf''  | url =https://www.golf.com/tour-and-news/jack-nicklaus-marks-passing-friend-valhalla-owner-dwight-gahm | title=Jack Nicklaus Marks Passing of Friend, Valhalla Founder Dwight Gahm |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* '' [[Dinah Shore]] Wall of Champions '' Relief sculpture (Bronze, Cantera stone | life size). Mission Hills Country Club and Resort, [[Rancho Mirage, California]]. Dedication: March 26, 1995. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Baldwin, Patricia, ''South Florida Sun-Sentinel'' | url =https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1995-03-26-9503250301-story.html | title=Wall of Champions is a Fitting Memorial to Dinah| accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* '' [[Robert H. Dedman Sr.]] '' Statue (Bronze | 7ft | sculpted from life). [[Pinehurst Resort]], [[North Carolina]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Waymarking'' | url =https://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMD79G_Robert_H_Dedman_Sr_Pinehurst_NC | title= Robert H. Dedman Sr. \u2013 Pinehurst, NC \u2013 Statues of Historic Figures| accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* '' [[Richard Tufts]] '' Statue (Bronze | over-life size). Walk of Fame, [[Pinehurst Resort]], [[North Carolina]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Waymarking'' | url =https://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMD738_Richard_Tufts_Pinehurst_Golf_Course_Pinehurst_NC | title= Richard Tufts \u2013 Pinehurst, NC \u2013 Statues of Historic Figures| accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* '' [[Bobby Jones (golfer)|Bob Jones]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). [[East Lake Golf Club]], [[Atlanta, Georgia]].\n* '' [[Bobby Jones (golfer)|Bob Jones]] '' Statue (Bronze | over-life-size). Georgia Golf Hall of Fame, [[Augusta, Georgia]]. <ref>{{Cite web| author= The Masters | url =http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/golf/masters01/2001-03-30-statues.html| title=Statues of Legends Find Home in New Augusta| accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n* '' [[Bobby Jones (golfer)|Bob Jones]] '' Distinguished Sportsman Award (Bronze | 18in). Bob Jones, [[U.S. Golf Association]] Museum.\n====Baseball====\n* '' [[Mike Schmidt]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size | sculpted from life). Private collection.\n* '' [[Mike Schmidt]] '' Statue (Bronze | 10 ft | sculpted from life). [[Citizens Bank Park]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n* '' [[Steve Carlton]] '' Statue (Bronze | 10 ft | sculpted from life). [[Citizens Bank Park]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n* '' [[Richie Ashburn]] '' Statue (Bronze | 10 ft | sculpted from life). [[Citizens Bank Park]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n* '' [[Robin Roberts]] '' Statue (Bronze | 10 ft | sculpted from life). [[Citizens Bank Park]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n* '' [[Joe DiMaggio]] and Young Boy '' Statue (Bronze | over-life-size | sculpted from life). DiMaggio Children's Hospital, [[Hollywood, Florida]].\n* '' [[Danny Murtaugh]] '' Relief sculpture, Boston Braves, 1947 (Bronze | relief). [[Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame | Athletes Hall of Fame]], [[Chadds Ford, Pennsylvania]].\n\n====Hockey====\n* '' [[Brian Propp]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). [[Philadelphia Flyers]] Hall of Fame. Additional casting in private collection.\n\n====Coaches====\n* '' Coach Fritz Brennan'' Statue (Bronze | 8ft). Lower Merion High School, [[Ardmore, Pennsylvania]], [[Chadds Ford, Pennsylvania]].\n* '' [[Ron Fraser|Coach Ron Fraser]] '' Statue (Bronze | 7ft). [[University of Miami]], [[Miami, Florida]].\n* '' Coach \u201cLake\u201d Staffieri '' Relief (Bronze | life size). Franklin Field, [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n\n\n\n===Statues===\n* '' [[Clarence Darrow]]''. Statue (Bronze | 7ft) [[Rhea County Courthouse]], [[Dayton, Tennessee]]. Dedication: July 14, 2017. <ref>{{Cite web| author= Fausset, Richard, New York Times | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/14/us/darrow-bryan-dayton-tennessee-scopes-statues.html| title=At Site of Scopes Trial, Darrow Statue Belatedly Joins Bryan\u2019s |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*''[[Frederick Law Olmsted]]''. Statue (Bronze, stone base | 8ft) Blue Ridge Court, [[The North Carolina Arboretum]], [[Asheville, North Carolina]]. Dedication: April 22, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Citizen Times | url =https://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2015/02/02/arboretum-prepares-olmsted-statue-expected-fall/22738735/ | title=Arboretum prepares for Olmsted statue |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* '' [[Michael Kahn (theatre director)|Michael Kahn]] '', former Artistic Director, Shakespeare Theatre Company. Statue (Bronze | life size) Sidney Harman Hall, [[Shakespeare Theatre Company]], [[Washington, DC.]] Private Collection. Completed: 2012.<ref>{{Cite web| author= Rosenstein, Peter, The Georgetown Dish | url =http://www.thegeorgetowndish.com/thedish/michael-kahn-leader-innovator-icon-friend | title=Michael Kahn; Leader, Innovator, Icon, Friend | accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n* '' [[John D. MacArthur]] '' Statue (Bronze, granite base | 8ft figure, 3ft base | 750lbs) [[Palm Beach Gardens]], [[North Palm Beach, Florida]]. Dedication: November 21, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web| author= DiPaolo, Bill, The Palm Beach Post | url =https://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/macarthur-statue-arrives-final-resting-place-palm-beach-gardens/KiAt4rqroyoAQbuUADKR1I/ | title=MacArthur statue arrives at final resting place in Palm Beach Gardens |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n\n===Portrait Busts===\n====Contemporary====\n* '' [[Philip Cohen]] '' Portrait bust (Clay, cast in plaster | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Don McLean]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Paul Girolami|Sir Paul Girolami]], CEO of Glaxo, Inc. '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Research Triangle Park, [[North Carolina]]; [[London, England]]; [[Tokyo, Japan]].\n* '' [[Edmund N. Bacon]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Nina Simone]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | over-life size). Private collection.\n* '' Sheila '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Museum of the Academy of Design, Permanent Collection. [[National Academy of Design]], [[New York, New York]].\n* '' Dr. Stone'' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). [[Temple University School of Medicine]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n* '' [[Norman Adrian Wiggins | Dr. Norman Adrian Wiggins]], President of Campbell University, 1967-2003'' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Dr. Norman Adrian Wiggins School of Law, [[Campbell University]], [[Raleigh, North Carolina]].\n* '' Samuel L. Evans'' Portrait bust (Bronze, wood base | life size). American Foundation for Negro Affairs (AFNA), [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. Dedication: May 27, 2015. <ref>{{Cite web| author= United States Golf Association | url =https://www.usga.org/content/usga/home-page/videos/2015/05/27/150527-nicklaus-room-wrap-4260846447001.html| title=Jack Nicklaus Room Opening|accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* '' [[John Sevier]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Sevier Public Library, King Family Library, Sevierville, Tennessee. Additional castings in private collections.\n* '' Rosalie Frudakis '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n\n====Government/Military====\n* '' [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Winston Churchill]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Alexander Hamilton]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Benjamin Franklin]] '' Portrait bust (Clay | life size). Work in progress.\n* '' [[John D. MacArthur]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze, granite base | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[A. A. Birch Jr. | Chief Justice Birch]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). [[Tennessee Supreme Court]], [[Nashville, Tennessee]].\n* '' [[William P. Yarborough|General Yarborough]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). [[Airborne & Special Operations Museum]], [[Fayetteville, North Carolina]].\n* '' [[K. Leroy Irvis]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). State Museum of Pennsylvania, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania. Additional castings in private collections.\n* '' [[Marine]] '' Portrait bust (Bronze | life size). Private collection.\n\n====Historic====\n* ''[[Mark Twain]]''. Portrait bust. (Bronze | over-life-size) The Lotos Club, [[New York City|New York]], New York.<ref>\"The Lotos Experience 1995 pp. 34-35\"</ref>\n* '' [[Albert Einstein]] '' Portrait bust (Clay | life size). Work in progress.\n* '' [[Dante]] '' Portrait bust (Clay | life size). Work in progress.\n* '' [[Edgar Allan Poe]] '' Portrait bust (Clay | life size). Work in progress.\n* '' [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]] '' Portrait bust (Clay | life size). Work in progress.\n* '' [[Alexis de Toqueville]] '' Portrait bust (Clay | life size). Private collection.\n* '' [[Amelia Earhart]] '' Portrait bust (Clay | life size). Work in progress.\n\n\n\n\n==Awards==\nFrudakis is a member of the prestigious [[National Sculpture Society]].<ref name=nss_fellow>{{Cite web| author=National Sculpture Society| url=https://nationalsculpture.org/author/zenos_frudakis/| title= Fellows of NSS |accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Frudakis was invited to participate in Japan's Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibition, where he won the Hakone Award at Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum.<ref>Third Rodin Grand Prize Exhibit, The Utsukushi-ga-hara Open Air Museum, Hakone Open Air Museum, Embassies of Greece, Spain, United Kingdom and British Consul, United States, West Germany, 1990, pp. 27-28.</ref> The Museum purchased a cast of Frudakis's sculpture ''Reaching''.<ref>Donald Reynolds, ''Masters of American Sculpture'' (Abbeville Press, 1993), p. 250.</ref>\n\nIn 1991 he was elected into the [[National Academy of Design]] as an Associate member, and became a full Academician in 1993.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:Zenos_Frudakis_Dream_To_Fly_Cherry_Hill.jpg|Dream to Fly, Cherry Hill, NJ -->\nImage:Knowledge is Power.jpg|thumb|Knowledge is Power.\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Gateway_to_Growth_in_progress.JPG|Gateway to Growth (in progress)\nImage:Chef Pep\u00edn, portrait sculpture and sculptor Zenos Frudakis.jpg|Chef Pepin, portrait sculpture and Frudakis\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_General_Yarborough_Fayetteville.JPG|General Yarborough, Airborne & Special Ops Museum, Fayetteville, NC\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Jack_Nicklaus_Louisville.jpg|[[Jack Nicklaus]], Dwight Gahm [[Valhalla Golf Club]], Louisville, KY\nImage:Dwight Eisenhower sculpture by Zenos Frudakis.jpg|thumb|Portrait sculpture of Dwight D. Eisenhower by Zenos Frudakis.\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mark_Twain_Lotos.jpg|[[Mark Twain]], The [[Lotos Club]], New York, NY\nImage:Nina Simone Plaza-Tryon NC-full-size-photo credit-Meg Rogers (2).jpg|Nina Simone Sculpture by Zenos Frudakis, Nina Simone Plaza in Tryon, NC. Photo credit: [[Meg Rogers]]\nImage:Zenos_Frudakis_Mike_Schmidt_Philadelphia.jpg|[[Mike Schmidt]], [[Citizens Bank Park]], Philadelphia, PA<ref name=mike_schmidt>{{Cite web|author=Citizens Bank Park|url=http://www.ballparkreviews.com/philly/cit.htm#|title=Citizens Bank Park|accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Carchidi|first=Sam|year=2004|title=Four legends honored with statues|periodical=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|issue=April 13|pages=F8}}</ref>\nImage:Zenos Frudakis Arnold Palmer Legioner.jpg|thumb|[[Arnold Palmer]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Appelbaum, David, and Mel Thompson, editors. ''World Philosophy''. Vega, 2002, pp.&nbsp;250\u201351.\n* Boyne, Walter J., Rosalie Frudakis, Katherine Jaeger, et al. ''The United States Air Force Memorial Honor Guard, A Sculpture by Zenos Frudakis''. Techni Press, 2007.\n* Dunhoff, Richard, and Philip H. Wagner. ''Philadelphia, A Photographic Portrait.'' Twin Lights Publishers, 2004, p.&nbsp;14.\n* Goode, James M. ''Washington Sculpture.'' Johns Hopkins University Press, 2008.\n* Gordon, Robert, and Tom Burgoyne. ''Movin' On Up''. MidAtlantic Press, 2004, pp.&nbsp;264\u201364.\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.zenosfrudakis.com}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Facebook]\n* [https://twitter.com/ZenosFrudakis Zenos Frudakis: Twitter]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frudakis, Zenos}}\n[[Category:American sculptors]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:People from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from California]]\n", "name_user": "Cher Skoubo", "label": "safe", "comment": "improving references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zenos_Frudakis"}
{"title_page": "Lillian Smith (author)", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Lillian Smith\n| embed = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Lillian Eugenia Smith NYWTS.jpg \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Lillian Eugenia Smith\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1897|12|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Jasper, Florida]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1966|9|28|1897|12|12}}\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = Laurel Falls: [[Clayton, Georgia]]\n| occupation = Writer\n| language = \n| nationality = American\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = American\n| education = [[Piedmont College]],<br> [[Peabody Conservatory]]\n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement = Civil Rights Movement\n| notableworks = ''Strange Fruit'' (novel) <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner = Paula Snelling \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n'''Lillian Eugenia Smith''' (December 12, 1897 \u2013 September 28, 1966) was a writer and social critic of the [[Southern United States]], known most prominently for her best-selling novel ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' (1944). A white woman who openly embraced controversial positions on matters of race and gender equality, she was a [[Southern United States|southern]] [[American liberalism|liberal]] unafraid to criticize [[Racial segregation|segregation]] and work toward the dismantling of [[Jim Crow laws]], at a time when such actions virtually guaranteed social ostracism.\n\n==Early life==\nSmith was born on December 12, 1897, to a prominent family in [[Jasper, Florida]], the seventh of nine children. Her life as the daughter of a middle-class civic and business leader took an abrupt turn in 1915 when her father lost his [[turpentine]] mills. The family was not without resources, however, and decided to relocate to their summer residence in the mountains of [[Clayton, Georgia|Clayton]], [[Georgia (US state)|Georgia]], where her father had previously purchased property and operated the Laurel Falls Camp for Girls.\n\nNow a young adult financially on her own, she was free to pursue her love of music and teaching for the next five years. She spent a year studying at [[Piedmont College]] in [[Demorest, Georgia|Demorest]], Georgia, (1915\u201316). She also had two stints at the [[Peabody Conservatory]] in [[Baltimore]] in 1917 and 1919. She returned home and helped her parents manage a hotel and taught in two mountain schools before accepting a position to be director of music at a [[Methodist]] school for girls in [[Huzhou]] (now Wuxing, [[Zhejiang]]), China. She was not a churchgoer and did not consider herself religious, however this time abroad gave way for a pivotal moment in Smith's awareness of the Southern [[double standard]]. She studied Chinese philosophy during her time overseas and by living in China was exposed to the similarities between the suppression of the Chinese and African Americans in the States.<ref name=Hobson>{{cite web|last1=Hobson|first1=Fred|title=The sins of the fathers: Lillian Smith and Katharine Du Pre Lumpkin|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/literary-criticism/1316731/sins-fathers-lillian-smith-katharine-du-pre-lumpkin|publisher=EBSCO|work=The Southern Review|accessdate=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer time in China was limited, however, by her father's declining health, so she was forced to return home to the States in 1925. Back in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], she assumed the role of heading the Laurel Falls Camp, a position she would hold for the next 23 years (1925\u201348). Laurel Falls Camp soon became very popular under her direction as an innovative educational institution known for its instruction in the arts, music, drama, and modern psychology. Her father died in 1930, and she was left with responsibility for the family business and the care of her ill mother.\n\n==Relationship and career==\nDuring her time at the family camp, Lillian Smith soon formed a lifelong relationship with one of the camp's school counselors, Paula Snelling, of [[Pinehurst, Georgia]]. The two remained closeted as a same-sex couple for the rest of their lives, as their correspondence has shown.<ref>Gladney, Margaret Rose, \"Personalizing the Political, Politicizing the Personal: Reflections on Editing the Letters of Lillian Smith\", in ''Carryin' On in the Lesbian and Gay South'', John Howard (ed.), New York and London: New York University Press, 1997, p. 102.</ref> In the South, gender roles were binarily distinct and Smith never addressed her sexuality openly. However, some of her literature's characters were lesbian. At that time, homosexuality was more of a taboo in Southern Society than desegregation.<ref name=Hobson /> Lillian and Paula began publishing a small, quarterly literary magazine, ''Pseudopodia'', in 1936. The magazine encouraged writers, black or white, to offer honest assessments of modern southern life, to challenge for social and economic reform, and it criticized those who ignored the Old South's poverty and injustices. It quickly gained regional fame as a forum for liberal thought, undergoing two name changes to reflect its expanding scope. In 1937 it became the ''North Georgia Review'', and in 1942, the title was changed to its final form, ''South Today''. ''South Today'' ceased publication in 1945.\n\nIn 1944, she published the bestselling novel ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'', which dealt with the then-forbidden and controversial theme of interracial romance. The title was originally ''Jordan is so Chilly'', with Smith later changing the title to ''Strange Fruit''. In her autobiography, singer [[Billie Holiday]] wrote that Smith chose to name the book after her song \"[[Strange Fruit]]\", which was about the lynching and racism against [[African-Americans]], although Smith maintained that the book's title referred to the \"damaged, twisted people (both black and white) who are the products or results of our racist culture.\"<ref name=SFP>{{cite book|editor1=Perkins, Kathy|editor2=Judith Stephens|title=Strange Fruit: Plays on Lynching by American Women|year=1998|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=0253211638|pages=222\u2013225|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G1il9uQG3A8C&q=strange+fruit#v=snippet&q=%22strange%20fruit%22&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"stover1944\">{{Cite news |last=Stover |first=Frances|title=Lillian Smith's 'Strange Fruit' stirs a storm |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AvAZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3016,4001421&dq=lillian-smith+strange-fruit&hl=en\n|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal |date=March 26, 1944 |page=3\n|accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref><ref name=CJohnson>{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Cheryl L.|title=The Language of Sexuality and Silence in Lillian Smith's ''Strange Fruit''|journal=Signs|date=Autumn 2001|volume= 27|issue= 1|pages=1\u201322|jstor=3175864|doi=10.1086/495668}}</ref> After the book's release, the book was [[banned in Boston]] and Detroit for \"lewdness\" and crude language.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hub Head Cop Blackens City In Book Ban|work=Billboard|date=April 1, 1944|pages=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TAwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT2&lpg=PT2&dq=%22Strange+Fruit%22+Lillian+Smith+banned&source=bl&ots=xRjAFG_ct5&sig=vdNiNdF9xJLX996Gr0kUiKr2Q1E&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e6N9UPyhMOTl0QGOwoHgAw&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAw}}</ref> ''Strange Fruit'' was also banned from being mailed through the U.S. Postal Service, with the ban against the book being lifted by [[President Franklin D. Roosevelt]] after his wife [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] requested it of him.<ref name=EGbook>{{cite book|last=Goldner|first=Ellen|title=Racing and (E)Racing Language: Living With the Color of Our Words|year=2001|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=0815628927|pages=100\u2013105|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fVYrTYyp98kC&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=%22Strange+Fruit%22+Lillian+Smith+banned&source=bl&ots=bqUkt9K6_A&sig=-7pF7DRej8so3Hjw44wA_sIlMeA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e6N9UPyhMOTl0QGOwoHgAw&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22Strange%20Fruit%22%20Lillian%20Smith%20banned&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn 1949, Smith kept up her personal assault on racism with ''Killers of the Dream'',<ref>Inscoe, John C., [http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/arts-culture/killers-dream \"Killers of the Dream\"], ''New Georgia Encyclopedia''.</ref> a collection of essays that attempted to identify, challenge and dismantle the Old South's racist traditions, customs and beliefs, warning that segregation corrupted the soul. She also emphasized the negative implications on the minds of women and children. Written in a confessional and autobiographical style that was highly critical of southern moderates, it met with something of a cruel silence from book critics and the literary community.\n\n==Civil Rights activism==\n\nOne of the ways Smith started openly discussing the problems of segregation was during her counseling of campers at Laurel Falls. It was this period of creative control over the camp that allowed her to use it as a place to discuss modern social issues, like the dangers of inequality and how to improve their society as women.<ref name=Heroines>{{cite web|last1=Michels|first1=Kat|title=Heroines of History: Lillian Smith - A Civil Rights Leader Ahead of her Time|url=http://businessheroinemagazine.com/lilliansmith/|website=Business Heroine Magazine|accessdate= May 7, 2017}}</ref> In 1955, the [[civil rights movement]] grabbed the entire nation's attention with the [[Montgomery bus boycott]]. By this time she had been meeting or corresponding with many southern blacks and liberal whites for years and was well aware of blacks' concerns. In response to [[Brown v. Board of Education]], the ruling that outlawed segregation in schools, she wrote ''Now Is the Time'' (1955), calling for compliance with the new court decision. She called the new ruling \"every child's [[Magna Carta]]\".\n\n==Death==\n\nSmith battled [[breast cancer]] from the early 1950s on and died on September 28, 1966, at the age of 68. Her book ''The Journey'' (1954) details some of this battle. She is buried near the old theater chimney, Laurel Falls camp atop Screamer Mountain, Clayton, Georgia.<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d edn: 2 (Kindle Locations 43992-43993). McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nToday, ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' remains her most famous work, translated into 15 languages, but many of her works, like ''Killers of the Dream'', are being rediscovered and given their due as groundbreaking in both style and substance. She no doubt deserves recognition as one of the first prominent Southern whites to write about and speak out openly against racism and segregation. Her lifelong convictions are summed up in her acceptance speech for the [[Charles S. Johnson]] Award at [[Fisk University]] in 1966: \"Segregation is evil; there is no pattern of life which can dehumanize men as can the way of segregation.\"\n\nIn 1999, Lillian Smith received the Georgia Women of Achievement Award.<ref>[https://www.georgiawomen.org/copy-of-sibley-celestine \"Lillian Eugenia Smith\"], Georgia Women of Achievement.</ref>\n\nSince 1968, the [[Lillian Smith Book Award]]s have been presented annually, except for 2003 when the Southern Regional Council experienced funding shortfalls.<ref>AP, [https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2004-02-12-lillian-book-awards_x.htm \"Lillian Smith Book Awards for works on social justice to be revived\"], ''USAToday'', February 12, 2004.<!-- Bot generated title --></ref> It is the South's oldest and best-known book award, and is presented in fiction and non-fiction categories.<ref name=Heroines /> It is meant to honor those authors who, through their outstanding writing about the American South, carry on Smith's legacy of elucidating the condition of racial and social inequity and proposing a vision of justice and human understanding. According to \"The Language of Sexuality and Silence in Lillian Smith's ''Strange Fruit''\", her work examines many different perspectives of American consciousness and is a great source to better understand Southern history post-Civil War through the Civil Rights Movement of the 1960s. She could also be used as a reliable patron for gay and lesbian research based on her relationship with Snelling.<ref name=CJohnson />\n\n==Selected works==\n*''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' (1944) {{ISBN|9781568494203}}, {{OCLC|184751847}}\n*''Killers of the Dream'', (1949) {{ISBN|9780393311600}}, {{OCLC|951462511}}\n*''The Journey'', New York: Norton,(1954) {{OCLC|745967889}}\n*''Now Is the Time'', New York: Viking Press (1955) {{ISBN|9781578066315}}. {{OCLC|53091211}}\n*''One Hour'', Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press (1959), {{OCLC|962028726}} \u2013 an attack on [[McCarthyism]] in the form of a novel\n*''Memory of a Large Christmas'', New York: Norton, (1962) {{ISBN|9780820318424}}. {{OCLC|53263972}}\n*''Our Faces, Our Words'', New York: W.W. Norton (1964), {{OCLC|558156250}} \u2013 an ode to the non-violent resistance of the [[civil rights movement]]\n\n==Collections==\n*''The Winner Names the Age: A Collection of Writings'', New York: Norton (1978) {{ISBN|9780393300444}}, {{OCLC|16501127}}\n*''How Am I to be Heard?: Letters of Lillian Smith'', Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press (1993) {{ISBN|9780807820957}}, {{OCLC|925154234}}\n*''A Lillian Smith Reader'', Athens: The University of Georgia Press (2016) {{ISBN|9780820349985}}, {{OCLC|965151015}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Louise Blackwell and Frances Clay, ''Lillian Smith''. New York: Twayne Publishers, Inc. 1971.\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Lillian Smith}}\n*[http://www.libs.uga.edu/hargrett/lilliansmith/lsmith.html Lillian Smith Book Award History @ University of Georgia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061002124315/http://www.nwhp.org/tlp/biographies/smith/smith_bio.html National Women's History Project biography section]\n*Bruce Clayton, [http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-463 \"Lillian Smith (1897-1966)\"], ''The New Georgia Encyclopedia''\n*[http://www.piedmont.edu/lillian-smith-center The Lillian E. Smith Center of Piedmont College]\n*[http://www.misslilscamp.com/biography.html Miss Lil's Camp - a documentary]\n*[https://lilliansmithdoc.com/ \"Lillian Smith: Breaking the Silence\" - a 2019 documentary]\n*[https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zwgt Lillian Eugenia Smith collection, 1940-1962]\n{{Georgia Women of Achievement}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Lillian}}\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Florida]]\n[[Category:LGBT novelists]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths from breast cancer]]\n[[Category:Peabody Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Jasper, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Clayton, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:American women essayists]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Piedmont College alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American essayists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Lillian Smith\n| embed = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Lillian Eugenia Smith NYWTS.jpg \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Lillian Eugenia Smith\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1897|12|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Jasper, Florida]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1966|9|28|1897|12|12}}\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = Laurel Falls: [[Clayton, Georgia]]\n| occupation = Writer\n| language = \n| nationality = American\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = American\n| education = [[Piedmont College]],<br> [[Peabody Conservatory]]\n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement = Civil Rights Movement\n| notableworks = ''Strange Fruit'' (novel) <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner = Paula Snelling \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n'''Lillian Eugenia Smith''' (December 12, 1897 \u2013 September 28, 1966) was a writer and social critic of the [[Southern United States]], known most prominently for her best-selling novel ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' (1944). A white woman who openly embraced controversial positions on matters of race and gender equality, she was a [[Southern United States|southern]] [[American liberalism|liberal]] unafraid to criticize [[Racial segregation|segregation]] and work toward the dismantling of [[Jim Crow laws]], at a time when such actions virtually guaranteed social ostracism.\n\n==Early life==\nSmith was born on December 12, 1897, to a prominent family in [[Jasper, Florida]], the seventh of nine children. Her life as the daughter of a middle-class civic and business leader took an abrupt turn in 1915 when her father lost his [[turpentine]] mills. The family was not without resources, however, and decided to relocate to their summer residence in the mountains of [[Clayton, Georgia|Clayton]], [[Georgia (US state)|Georgia]], where her father had previously purchased property and operated the Laurel Falls Camp for Girls.\n\nNow a young adult financially on her own, she was free to pursue her love of music and teaching for the next five years. She spent a year studying at [[Piedmont College]] in [[Demorest, Georgia|Demorest]], Georgia, (1915\u201316). She also had two stints at the [[Peabody Conservatory]] in [[Baltimore]] in 1917 and 1919. She returned home and helped her parents manage a hotel and taught in two mountain schools before accepting a position to be director of music at a [[Methodist]] school for girls in [[Huzhou]] (now Wuxing, [[Zhejiang]]), China. She was not a churchgoer and did not consider herself religious, however this time abroad gave way for a pivotal moment in Smith's awareness of the Southern [[double standard]]. She studied Chinese philosophy during her time overseas and by living in China was exposed to the similarities between the suppression of the Chinese and African Americans in the States.<ref name=Hobson>{{cite web|last1=Hobson|first1=Fred|title=The sins of the fathers: Lillian Smith and Katharine Du Pre Lumpkin|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/literary-criticism/1316731/sins-fathers-lillian-smith-katharine-du-pre-lumpkin|publisher=EBSCO|work=The Southern Review|accessdate=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer time in China was limited, however, by her father's declining health, so she was forced to return home to the States in 1925. Back in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], she assumed the role of heading the Laurel Falls Camp, a position she would hold for the next 23 years (1925\u201348). Laurel Falls Camp soon became very popular under her direction as an innovative educational institution known for its instruction in the arts, music, drama, and modern psychology. Her father died in 1930, and she was left with responsibility for the family business and the care of her ill mother.\n\n==Relationship and career==\nDuring her time at the family camp, Lillian Smith soon formed a lifelong relationship with one of the camp's school counselors, Paula Snelling, of [[Pinehurst, Georgia]]. The two remained closeted as a same-sex couple for the rest of their lives, as their correspondence has shown.<ref>Gladney, Margaret Rose, \"Personalizing the Political, Politicizing the Personal: Reflections on Editing the Letters of Lillian Smith\", in ''Carryin' On in the Lesbian and Gay South'', John Howard (ed.), New York and London: New York University Press, 1997, p. 102.</ref> In the South, gender roles were binarily distinct and Smith never addressed her sexuality openly. However, some of her literature's characters were lesbian. At that time, homosexuality was more of a taboo in Southern Society than desegregation.<ref name=Hobson /> Lillian and Paula began publishing a small, quarterly literary magazine, ''Pseudopodia'', in 1936. The magazine encouraged writers, black or white, to offer honest assessments of modern southern life, to challenge for social and economic reform, and it criticized those who ignored the Old South's poverty and injustices. It quickly gained regional fame as a forum for liberal thought, undergoing two name changes to reflect its expanding scope. In 1937 it became the ''North Georgia Review'', and in 1942, the title was changed to its final form, ''South Today''. ''South Today'' ceased publication in 1945.\n\nIn 1944, she published the bestselling novel ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'', which dealt with the then-forbidden and controversial theme of interracial romance. The title was originally ''Jordan is so Chilly'', with Smith later changing the title to ''Strange Fruit''. In her autobiography, singer [[Billie Holiday]] wrote that Smith chose to name the book after her song \"[[Strange Fruit]]\", which was about the lynching and racism against [[African-Americans]], although Smith maintained that the book's title referred to the \"damaged, twisted people (both black and white) who are the products or results of our racist culture.\"<ref name=SFP>{{cite book|editor1=Perkins, Kathy|editor2=Judith Stephens|title=Strange Fruit: Plays on Lynching by American Women|year=1998|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=0253211638|pages=222\u2013225|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G1il9uQG3A8C&q=strange+fruit#v=snippet&q=%22strange%20fruit%22&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"stover1944\">{{Cite news |last=Stover |first=Frances|title=Lillian Smith's 'Strange Fruit' stirs a storm |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AvAZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BCMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3016,4001421&dq=lillian-smith+strange-fruit&hl=en\n|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal |date=March 26, 1944 |page=3\n|accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref><ref name=CJohnson>{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Cheryl L.|title=The Language of Sexuality and Silence in Lillian Smith's ''Strange Fruit''|journal=Signs|date=Autumn 2001|volume= 27|issue= 1|pages=1\u201322|jstor=3175864|doi=10.1086/495668}}</ref> After the book's release, the book was [[banned in Boston]] and Detroit for \"lewdness\" and crude language.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hub Head Cop Blackens City In Book Ban|work=Billboard|date=April 1, 1944|pages=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TAwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT2&lpg=PT2&dq=%22Strange+Fruit%22+Lillian+Smith+banned&source=bl&ots=xRjAFG_ct5&sig=vdNiNdF9xJLX996Gr0kUiKr2Q1E&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e6N9UPyhMOTl0QGOwoHgAw&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAw}}</ref> ''Strange Fruit'' was also banned from being mailed through the U.S. Postal Service, with the ban against the book being lifted by [[President Franklin D. Roosevelt]] after his wife [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] requested it of him.<ref name=EGbook>{{cite book|last=Goldner|first=Ellen|title=Racing and (E)Racing Language: Living With the Color of Our Words|year=2001|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=0815628927|pages=100\u2013105|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fVYrTYyp98kC&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=%22Strange+Fruit%22+Lillian+Smith+banned&source=bl&ots=bqUkt9K6_A&sig=-7pF7DRej8so3Hjw44wA_sIlMeA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=e6N9UPyhMOTl0QGOwoHgAw&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22Strange%20Fruit%22%20Lillian%20Smith%20banned&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn 1949, Smith kept up her personal assault on racism with ''Killers of the Dream'',<ref>Inscoe, John C., [http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/arts-culture/killers-dream \"Killers of the Dream\"], ''New Georgia Encyclopedia''.</ref> a collection of essays that attempted to identify, challenge and dismantle the Old South's racist traditions, customs and beliefs, warning that segregation corrupted the soul. She also emphasized the negative implications on the minds of women and children. Written in a confessional and autobiographical style that was highly critical of southern moderates, it met with something of a cruel silence from book critics and the literary community.\n\n==Civil Rights activism==\n\nOne of the ways Smith started openly discussing the problems of segregation was during her counseling of campers at Laurel Falls. It was this period of creative control over the camp that allowed her to use it as a place to discuss modern social issues, like the dangers of inequality and how to improve their society as women.<ref name=Heroines>{{cite web|last1=Michels|first1=Kat|title=Heroines of History: Lillian Smith - A Civil Rights Leader Ahead of her Time|url=http://businessheroinemagazine.com/lilliansmith/|website=Business Heroine Magazine|accessdate= May 7, 2017}}</ref> In 1955, the [[civil rights movement]] grabbed the entire nation's attention with the [[Montgomery bus boycott]]. By this time she had been meeting or corresponding with many southern blacks and liberal whites for years and was well aware of blacks' concerns. In response to [[Brown v. Board of Education]], the ruling that outlawed segregation in schools, she wrote ''Now Is the Time'' (1955), calling for compliance with the new court decision. She called the new ruling \"every child's [[Magna Carta]]\".\n\n==Death==\n\nSmith battled [[breast cancer]] from the early 1950s on and died on September 28, 1966, at the age of 68. Her book ''The Journey'' (1954) details some of this battle. She is buried near the old theater chimney, Laurel Falls camp atop Screamer Mountain, Clayton, Georgia.<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d edn: 2 (Kindle Locations 43992-43993). McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nToday, ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' remains her most famous work, translated into 15 languages, but many of her works, like ''Killers of the Dream'', are being rediscovered and given their due as groundbreaking in both style and substance. She no doubt deserves recognition as one of the first prominent Southern whites to write about and speak out openly against racism and segregation. Her lifelong convictions are summed up in her acceptance speech for the [[Charles S. Johnson]] Award at [[Fisk University]] in 1966: \"Segregation is evil; there is no pattern of life which can dehumanize men as can the way of segregation.\"\n\nIn 1999, Lillian Smith received the Georgia Women of Achievement Award.<ref>[https://www.georgiawomen.org/copy-of-sibley-celestine \"Lillian Eugenia Smith\"], Georgia Women of Achievement.</ref>\n\nSince 1968, the [[Lillian Smith Book Award]]s have been presented annually, except for 2003 when the Southern Regional Council experienced funding shortfalls.<ref>AP, [https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2004-02-12-lillian-book-awards_x.htm \"Lillian Smith Book Awards for works on social justice to be revived\"], ''USAToday'', February 12, 2004.<!-- Bot generated title --></ref> It is the South's oldest and best-known book award, and is presented in fiction and non-fiction categories.<ref name=Heroines /> It is meant to honor those authors who, through their outstanding writing about the American South, carry on Smith's legacy of elucidating the condition of racial and social inequity and proposing a vision of justice and human understanding. According to \"The Language of Sexuality and Silence in Lillian Smith's ''Strange Fruit''\", her work examines many different perspectives of American consciousness and is a great source to better understand Southern history post-Civil War through the Civil Rights Movement of the 1960s. She could also be used as a reliable patron for gay and lesbian research based on her relationship with Snelling.<ref name=CJohnson />\n\n==Selected works==\n*''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' (1944) {{ISBN|9781568494203}}, {{OCLC|184751847}}\n*''Killers of the Dream'', (1949) {{ISBN|9780393311600}}, {{OCLC|951462511}}\n*''The Journey'', New York: Norton,(1954) {{OCLC|745967889}}\n*''Now Is the Time'', New York: Viking Press (1955) {{ISBN|9781578066315}}. {{OCLC|53091211}}\n*''One Hour'', Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press (1959), {{OCLC|962028726}} \u2013 an attack on [[McCarthyism]] in the form of a novel\n*''Memory of a Large Christmas'', New York: Norton, (1962) {{ISBN|9780820318424}}. {{OCLC|53263972}}\n*''Our Faces, Our Words'', New York: W.W. Norton (1964), {{OCLC|558156250}} \u2013 an ode to the non-violent resistance of the [[civil rights movement]]\n\n==Collections==\n*''The Winner Names the Age: A Collection of Writings'', New York: Norton (1978) {{ISBN|9780393300444}}, {{OCLC|16501127}}\n*''How Am I to be Heard?: Letters of Lillian Smith'', Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press (1993) {{ISBN|9780807820957}}, {{OCLC|925154234}}\n*''A Lillian Smith Reader'', Athens: The University of Georgia Press (2016) {{ISBN|9780820349985}}, {{OCLC|965151015}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Louise Blackwell and Frances Clay, ''Lillian Smith''. New York: Twayne Publishers, Inc. 1971.\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Lillian Smith}}\n*